<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,152,755]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,369,395]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Young &amp; Skevington &amp; Steenis" authorityYear="2020" box="[583,692,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Psilota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscifrons">
<emphasis box="[583,692,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">fuscifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ consists of 
<emphasis box="[833,895,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">fusci-</emphasis>
, derived from the Latin for “dark, dusky” (‘fuscus’), and 
<emphasis box="[269,334,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">-frons</emphasis>
, the Latin for frons (‘frons, -ntis’). This is in reference to the entrensive dark pilosity of the frons.
</paragraph>
